04","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1180":"1180","Épinal, Vosges, Grand Est, France":"Épinal, Vosges, Grand Est, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1200–":"1200–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1204–Female":"1204–Deceased","1235–Male":"1235–Deceased","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1204":"1204","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1180":"1180","Épinal, Vosges, Grand Est, France":"Épinal, Vosges, Grand Est, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Déville in Seine-Maritime, France, probably named with Latin <i>dei villa</i> ‘settlement of (i.e. under the protection of) God’. This name was interpreted early on as a prepositional phrase <i>de ville</i> or <i>de val</i> and applied to dwellers in a town or valley (  see  Ville   and   Vale  ).","2  English: nickname from Middle English <i>devyle</i>, Old English <i>dēofol</i> ‘devil’ (Latin <i>diabolus</i>, from Greek <i>diabolos</i> ‘slanderer’, ‘enemy’), referring to a mischievous youth or perhaps to someone who had acted the role of the Devil in a pageant or mystery play.","3  French: variant of   Ville  , with the preposition <i>de</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Devall","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Déville in Seine-Maritime. The full form was <i>de Daiville</i> but when the preposition was omitted, <i>Daiville</i> was taken to be for <i>de Aiville</i>.","English: alternatively the name may be from Middle English <i>devel</i> (Old English <i>dēofol</i>) ‘devil, Satan’, possibly acquired as a pageant name or as a shortened form of a longer nickname; compare   Deeble  .","Altered form of French   Duval   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname. Compare   Duvall  ."]},{"name":"Vale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Abilio, Angel, Fernando, Jose Joel, Miguel, Pedro, Roberto, Adriana, Alberto, Alfredo.","English: of Norman origin, a topographic name for someone who lived ‘(in the) vale or valley’ (Middle English <i>val(e)</i>, <i>valle</i>, Old French <i>val</i> ‘valley’), or a habitational name for someone who came from one of the French places called with this word, such as Le Val (Sarthe) or any number of places in and around Normandy called Vaux. Compare   Vause  .","Irish: from <b>Mac Pháil</b> ‘son of Paul’."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume De Ville was born in 1200, his father, Erard de Ville I, was 26 and his mother, Elizabeth de Bourgogne Montague, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Constance de Zoehringen de Ville."},"et":{"1200–":"1200–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1204–Female":"1204–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1204":"1204","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1180":"1180","Épinal, Vosges, Grand Est, France":"Épinal, Vosges, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1200–":"1200–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1204–Female":"1204–Kuollut","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","1175–Male":"1175–Kuollut","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1204":"1204","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1180":"1180","Épinal, Vosges, Grand Est, France":"Épinal, Vosges, Grand Est, Ranska"},"fr":{"1200–":"1200–Décédé","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1204–Female":"1204–Décédée","1235–Male":"1235–Décédé","1175–Male":"1175–Décédé","1180–Female":"1180–Décédée","1204":"1204","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1180":"1180","Épinal, Vosges, Grand Est, France":"Épinal, Vosges, Grand Est, France","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Guillaume De Ville est né en 1200, son père, Erard de Ville I, avait 26 ans et sa mère, Elizabeth de Bourgogne Montague, avait 21 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Constance de Zoehringen de Ville."},"de":{"1200–":"1200–Verstorben","1200–Male":"1200–Verstorben","1204–Female":"1204–Verstorben","1235–Male":"1235–Verstorben","1175–Male":"1175–Verstorben","1180–Female":"1180–Verstorben","1204":"1204","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1180":"1180","Épinal, Vosges, Grand Est, France":"Épinal, Vosges, Großer Osten, Frankreich","lifeSummary":"Als Guillaume De Ville 1200 geboren wurde, war sein Vater Erard de Ville I 26 und seine Mutter Elizabeth de Bourgogne Montague 21. Er hatte mit Constance de Zoehringen de Ville mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"1200–":"1200–Desede","1200–Male":"1200–Desede","1204–Female":"1204–Desede","1